<DOC><DOCNO> AP890921-0280 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1921EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-UAL     09-21 0222</FIRST><SECOND>AM-UAL,0232</SECOND><HEAD>UAL Buyout Cost Could Reach $9.45 Billion</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Texas Air-GM, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The total cost of the UAL Corp. buyout could reach$9.45 billion, according to Securities and Exchange Commissionfilings by the employee-managment group seeking to take over UnitedAirlines' parent.   The group, composed of United pilots, UAL's top management andBritish Airways PLC, also announced in newspaper ads Thursday thecommencement of their tender offer for all outstanding shares ofUAL's common stock for $300 a share.   According to the merger agreement filed with the SEC onWednesday, the buyout group will require $6.8 billion to purchaseUAL's 22.65 million fully diluted shares.   It said the group may refinance $950 million in existing UALdebt, which would leave $512 million in long-term debt and $411million in capital leases outstanding.   Various fees and a $1.3 billion credit facility for workingcapital are also included in the total buyout cost.   The buyout, accepted by UAL's board of directors Sept. 14, willgive UAL workers 75 percent ownership of the company. Managementwill own 10 percent and British Airways will own 15 percent.   The group plans to finance the transaction with $750 million fromBritish Airways, $200 million in voluntary pension contributionsfrom the pilots, $1.3 billion from UAL cash reserves and $7.2billion in bank loans.</TEXT></DOC>